Black cod used to be plentiful in our waters but have diminished to such an extent to be a rare find in recent years. With solid protections now in place, we are now starting to see more of them. This is the fourth individual we have seen in Sydney over the last two years; it is estimated at 80 cm and has been seen several times in the sanctuary zone at Shelly Beach, Sydney.

Grey or blue morwong are far less common than their red cousins. They are in serious decline; commercial fish catches in NSW have fallen from 600 t/yr in the '80s to less than 100 t/yr in recent times. Whilst they can grow to 80 cm, it is rare to find one less than half that size today. If you see these in a fish shop (often called "deep sea bream") don't buy them!

Brown sabretooth blennies like pretty much anything that has an opening for a home... like this Fanta can at Chowder Bay. For this reason, when doing a cleanup, it's important to check for criiters before removing containers. Plastic should always be removed, as it eventually breaks up into microplastics, but glass bottles with critters inside can be left in situ.

Dusky flathead usually lie hidden on the sandy bottom. When they decide to move, they arch up and spread their fins as you can see in this shot; milliseconds later the fish was in flight. 
Fairy Bower
The fish at Fairy Bower are bigger than I've ever seen; bream, whiting, and flathead in particular. This big female is over 60 cm long!

Female flathead are almost twice the size of males at maturity; a sexually mature male averages 31 cm whereas the female is 56 cm. Legal catch length is 36 cm which protects only 5% of breeding females (Gray and Barnes 2008).

Every autumn the dusky whalers visit Cabbage Tree Bay. According to locals it's when the water is at 21 degrees. There were half a dozen at Fairy Bower this week; this female was about 1.2 m long and could one day reach 3 m. It's a real privilege to see this migratory species in local waters; it is listed as near threatened or vulnerable by IUCN as its numbers have fallen rapidly in recent years. It is targeted worldwide by commercial and recreational fishers and does not reach sexual maturity until 20 years of age, making it particularly susceptible to human pressures

This adolescent dusky was zooming around Shelly Beach, Sydney... v. sad to see it training a line from a hook embedded in it's mouth. Necropsies of sharks often find more hooks internally.  Let's hope this hook comes loose and doesn't become infected. A good argument for barbless hooks.

The dwarf lionfish is only a couple of inches long. It likes to tuck into nooks, like amongst sponge fronds or next to other sessile growth, often on a vertical face. This shot has been rotated; the original is vertical with the face downwards. Camp Cove, Sydney Harbour

Mado are the native mice of the seas of SE Australia. They form the critical link between primary producers and higher trophic levels as they feed primarily on plankton (phyto- and zoo-). Like noisy miners in our skies, they have benefited from human impacts on their environment..

The ringscale triplefin is often found darting about on pylons and rocks. At first glance the bright colouration of the male doesn't make sense - surely this makes it more likely to be eaten by predators? Yes it does, but like all evolutionary traits, it's a trade off. The male succeeds in life by surviving and passing on it's genes, and the latter is made more likely by the bright colouration. Females are more likely to mate with a bright male. Females don't have to worry about being chosen by a mate, and they are very hard to see with mottled brown colouration. Ain't nature wonderful! Clifton Gardens, Sydney Harbour

Another tricky ID - is this A nigropunctatus or stellatus? According to WoRMS, the golden puffer (A citrinellus) has been synonymised with the black-spotted puffer (A nigropunctatus) and has a yellow spotted variant. This brightly coloured male is an exception; juveniles and females are kelp-coloured with variable white spots. Only the male has the toothbrush "bristles" you can see here on the rear side of the body. Shark Point, Clovelly
Bare Island

I've often been asked why the toothbrush leatherjacket is named as it is. Most of the time it's hard to see why - unless you find a mature male. Then you can see the "bristles" along the caudal peduncle, like in this shot. Fairy Bower

A common fish in warm temperate waters, the white ear parma is a member of the Damselfish family. Damselfishes are widespread throughout the tropics and include humbugs, sergeant majors, tropical damsels and chromis. Fairy Bower

The most common seahorse around Sydney; this one is living on the nets at Clifton Gardens

Seahorses are actually fish that have evolved to occupy a particular niche in the marine environment. Their adaptations include bony body armour, amazing camouflage, an unusual mode of reproduction where the male broods the young in a pouch and a prehensile tail that can grasp the seaweeds in which they live.

The tiny white spots on this young individual are one characteristic of the species. The base colour can vary from cream to dark grey. The species is named after John White, Surgeon-General on the First Fleet. He would have sailed right past the spot where this photo was taken at Chowder Bay.

This tiny fish (about 1 cm long) was hovering around a rock ledge at Bare Island. I trained my focus light on it to take a few shots, and out of the darkness came a white-ear parma looking for a feed or a territorial dispute. The little boxfish darted for cover just in time. I quickly turned off my light; clearly I was exposing the little guy to risk of predation. I did, however, get this shot in first

Another tropical visitor in Sydney; the purple rock cod is normally found in tropical Australia. The most southern sighting in Reef Life Survey is Port Stephens, but a specimen was caught in Sydney Harbour in 1991. The juvenile in this photo was flitting around at Shiprock, Port Hacking in October 2016. Photo captured from high definition video.

The amount of time I have waited in front of an anglerfish finger on the trigger waiting for it to display a behaviour other than sitting waiting for lunch to swim by would be hours. Today however was the exception as this awesome little fella pulled out the repertoire time and again. With Pete McGee.

"Gone fishing"
They are not called an angler for nothing. They wave their little lure with its worm like bait around hoping for prey to be drawn in ready to feed on the unsuspected prey.

"Gulp"
After a spot of fishing he decided to start gulping in water. It got so bloated it was rolling around in the water. Not sure on why it did this but many species will often look to enlarge themselves as a mechanism of protection so it may well be a defensive move.

"Yawn"
The yawn is an example of how it would open its mouth and look to suck in the prey in an instantaneous motion giving its prey no chance. They are able to ingest large victims compared to their own size this way.
